snippet.textDisplay:
[Note: I'm using a composite of all Links here]

Thing is, this isn't even Link's greatest lifting feat. If we compare him to the Four Giants from Majora's Mask, that means he could probably hold back the moon. With that said, this doesn't make him the strongest video game character. In fact, he's not even the strongest Nintendo character.

First off, while measuring lifting strength can be useful, more accurate measures of strength are striking strength and attack potency. Fortunately for Link, his striking strength is on the universal level, being able to contend with Majora, Demise, and Ganon when he had the full Triforce. However, other Nintendo characters have exhibited similar, if not stronger feats.

For example, Ness from Earthbound was able to exert his power across all of space and time, giving him infinite third dimensional power and universal fourth dimensional power. Shulk from Xenoblade Chronicles could reset his universe by the end of the game. Rosalina at the end of Mario Galaxy also reset the universe. Going beyond Nintendo characters, Sonic in his Super form could take on fourth dimensional threats like Solaris, the Egg Wizard, and the Time Eater.

While the various Links are very powerful, there are many other video game characters that outclass them. Suggesting that Link is one of the strongest video game characters feels a bit like clickbait, especially when this video doesn't even use the Link's greatest feat.
